city and follow a typical pattern whereby a man or men take advantage of a woman's momentary or permanent vulnerability. Beyond describing the scope and variety of harassing behaviors, the book investigates the different ways women and men respond to and interpret them.Gardner concludes, provocatively, that gender-based public harassment exerts a powerful control over women's feelings of comfort in the towns and communities where they live and work. Further, she defines it as a new category of social problem that shares much in common with sexual harassment and, in its more menacing form, requires legal remedy.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEtiquettexIndianaxIndianapolis. 0aEtiquettezIndianazIndianapolis. 0aInvectivexIndianaxIndianapolis. 0aInvectivezIndianazIndianapolis. 0aSexual harassment of womenxIndianaxIndianapolis. 0aSexual harassment of womenzIndianazIndianapolis. 0aWomenxCrimes againstxIndianaxIndianapolisxIndianaxIndianapolis. 0aWomenxCrimes againstzIndianazIndianapolis. 4aGender Studies. 4aSocial Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aBrooks Gardner, Carol, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020215340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091683840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520916838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520916838/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles